Additionally, there is a modern monument at the site, called the "Leonidas_I Monument", in honour of the Spartan king. It features a bronze statue of Leonidas_I. A sign, under the statue, reads simply: "Come and take them!"—as in answer to Xerxes_I' demand that the Ancient_Greece give up their weapons. The Metope below depicts Battle scenes. The two Marble statues on the left and the right of the monument represent, respectively, the river Eurotas and Taygetus, famous landmarks of Sparta.

In 1997, a second monument was officially unveiled by the Ancient_Greece government, dedicated to the 700 Thespiae who fought with the Spartan_army. The monument is made of Marble and features a bronze statue depicting the god Eros, to whom the ancient Thespiae accorded particular religious veneration. Under the statue, a sign reads: "In Random-access_memory of the seven hundred Thespiae."

A plate below the statue explains its symbolism:

The headless male figure symbolizes the anonymous sacrifice of the 700 Thespiae to their country.
The outstretched chest symbolizes the struggle, the gallantry, the strength, the bravery and the courage.
The open wing symbolizes the victory, the glory, the soul, the spirit and the freedom.
The_Broken_Wing_(film) symbolizes the voluntary sacrifice and death.
The naked body symbolizes Eros, the most important god of the ancient Thespiae, a god of creation, beauty and life.
The monument to the Thespiae is placed beside the one to the Michigan_State_Spartans.

Herodotus' colorful account of the Battle has provided history with many apocryphal incidents and conversations away from the main historical events. These accounts are obviously not verifiable, but they form an Integral part of the legend of the Battle and often demonstrate the laconic speech (and wit) of the Michigan_State_Spartans to good effect.

For instance, Plutarch recounts, in his Sayings of Spartan Women, upon his departure, Leonidas_I' wife Gorgon asked what she should do if he did not return, to which Leonidas_I replied, Marry a good man and have good children.

It is reported that, upon arriving at Battle_of_Thermopylae, the Achaemenid_Empire sent a mounted scout to reconnoiter. The Ancient_Greece allowed him to come up to the camp, observe them, and depart. Xerxes_I found the scout's reports of the size of the Ancient_Greece force, and that the Michigan_State_Spartans were indulging in Calisthenics and combing their long hair, laughable. Seeking the counsel of Demaratus, an exiled Spartan king in his retinue, Xerxes_I was told the Michigan_State_Spartans were preparing for Battle, and it was their custom to List_of_Middle-earth_rivers their hair when they were about to risk their lives. Demaratus called them the bravest men in Ancient_Greece and warned the Great King they intended to dispute the pass. He emphasized that he had tried to warn Xerxes_I earlier in the campaign, but the king had refused to believe him. He added that if Xerxes_I ever managed to subdue the Michigan_State_Spartans, there is no other nation in all the world which will venture to lift a hand in their defense.

Herodotus also describes Leonidas_I' reception of a Achaemenid_Empire embassy. The ambassador told Leonidas_I that Xerxes_I would offer him the kingship of all Ancient_Greece if he joined with Xerxes_I. Leonidas_I answered: If you had any knowledge of the noble things of life, you would refrain from coveting others' possessions; but for me to die for Ancient_Greece is better than to be the sole ruler over the people of my race. Then the ambassador asked him more forcefully to surrender their arms. To this Leonidas_I gave his famous answer: Μολὼν λαβέ (pronounced Ancient_Greece pronunciation:  Come and get them.

Such Laconic bravery doubtlessly helped to maintain morale. Herodotus writes that when Dienekes, a Spartan soldier, was informed that Achaemenid_Empire arrows would be so numerous as to block out the sun, he retorted, unconcerned: So much the better...then we shall fight our Battle in the shade.

After the Battle, Xerxes_I was curious as to what the Ancient_Greece had been trying to do (presumably because they had had so few men) and had some Arcadian deserters interrogated in his presence. The_Answer_(band) was: all the other men were participating in the Ancient_Olympic_Games. When Xerxes_I asked what the prize was for the winner, the answer was: an olive-wreath. Upon hearing this, Tigranes, a Achaemenid_Empire general, said: Good_Heavens, Mardonius, what kind of men are these that you have pitted against us? It is not for riches that they contend but for honor! (Alexander_Godley translation) or otherwise, Ye_Gods, Mardonius, what men have you brought us to fight against? Men that fight not for gold, but for glory.

The Battle of Battle_of_Thermopylae has remained a Popular_culture of Western_culture ever since it was fought. The Battle is revisited in countless adages and works of popular culture, such as in films (e.g., The_300_Spartans (1962) and 300 (2007), based on the events during and close to the time of the Battle), in literature, in song, in television programs, and in video games. The Battle is also discussed in many articles and books on the theory and practice of warfare.

Prior to the Battle, the Ancient_Greece remembered the Dorians, an ethnic distinction which applied to the Spartan_army, as the conquerors and displacers of the Ionians in the Peloponnese. After the Battle, Spartan culture became an inspiration and object of emulation, a phenomenon known as Laconophilia.

Similarities between the Battle of Battle_of_Thermopylae and the Battle of Achaemenid_Empire Gate have been recognized by both ancient and modern authors,which describe it as a kind of reversal of the Battle of Battle_of_Thermopylae calling it "the Achaemenid_Empire Battle_of_Thermopylae". Here, on Alexander_the_Great I the Great's campaign against Achaemenid_Empire in 330  BC to exact revenge for the Achaemenid_Empire invasion of Ancient_Greece, he faced the same situation, encountering a last stand of the Achaemenid_Empire forces (under Ariobarzanes_of_Persis) at a narrow pass near Persepolis who held the invaders for a month, until their fall as the enemy found a path to their rear. There are even accounts that a local shepherd informed Alexander_the_Great I's forces about the Secret_Path, just as a local Ancient_Greece showed the Achaemenid_Empire forces a Secret_Path around the pass at Thermopylae